│ away (beyond 2^32). Alive2 reports a mismatch in memory: the vector store     │
│ overwrites memory at offset 17 (bytes) with 3, which did not happen in the    │
│ source program. This indicates an illegal coalescing of non-consecutive       │
│ stores.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe debug log shows \"Analyzing a store   │
│ chain of length 4\" and then vectorizes them: \"Decided to vectorize cost =   │
│ -2\" and emits a vector store. There is no evidence that the pass verified    │
│ that the store addresses form a single contiguous block with stride equal to  │
│ the element size. The sorting and grouping logic for stores uses              │
│ RelatedStoreInsts and getPointersDiff with StrictCheck=true in multiple       │
│ places to compute distances, but during the final decision path in            │
│ vectorizeStores (lines ~20990-21240), the code relies on cost and             │
│ profitability without revalidating that the stores in the selected chain are  │
│ truly consecutive. The SCEV-based heuristics for GEP costs and pointer chains │
│ (e.g., getGEPCosts) are cost modeling only, not legality.\n\n3. Root Cause    │
│ Analysis:\nThe root cause is a missing legality check in the store chain      │
│ vectorization path. The code computes costs and, if profitable, immediately   │
│ vectorizes (R.vectorizeTree()) without ensuring the selected stores are laid  │
│ out consecutively in memory. In the presence of large GEP offsets (e.g.,      │
│ 4294967312), the heuristics can mislead cost to be favorable; but             │
│ transforming into one wide store is only legal when the stores are to a       │
│ single contiguous region with element-size stride and same underlying object. │
│ Although RelatedStoreInsts computes pointer distances using getPointersDiff(… │
│ StrictCheck=true), this information is not re-validated before committing to  │
│ the transformation. As a result, non-consecutive stores pass through and get  │
│ vectorized into a single wide store, causing memory miscompares.\n\n4.        │
